1
00:00:01,320 --> 00:00:04,340
INSTRUCTOR: Welcome visitors
to this adventure guide,

2
00:00:04,340 --> 00:00:09,520
where you will learn how to
leverage your data by sorts,

3
00:00:09,520 --> 00:00:12,800
filters, and sets, oh my!

4
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:15,960
Often students get
intimidated by some

5
00:00:15,960 --> 00:00:19,040
of the powerful
tools in Tableau,

6
00:00:19,040 --> 00:00:23,260
and I can think of another
group of individuals

7
00:00:23,260 --> 00:00:28,780
who made themselves afraid just
simply by saying the words.

8
00:00:28,780 --> 00:00:30,293
Well, watch this short clip.

9
00:00:30,293 --> 00:00:30,960
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

10
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:32,780
- Lions and tigers and bears!

11
00:00:32,780 --> 00:00:33,920
Oh, my!

12
00:00:33,920 --> 00:00:36,820
Lions and tigers and bears!

13
00:00:36,820 --> 00:00:37,800
Oh, my!

14
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:39,900
Lions and tigers and bears!

15
00:00:39,900 --> 00:00:40,600
Oh, my!

16
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:42,340
Lions and tigers and bears!

17
00:00:42,340 --> 00:00:42,880
Oh, my!

18
00:00:42,880 --> 00:00:44,500
Lions and tigers and bears!

19
00:00:44,500 --> 00:00:45,928
Oh, my!

20
00:00:45,928 --> 00:00:47,103
[END PLAYBACK]

21
00:00:47,103 --> 00:00:48,020
INSTRUCTOR: All right.

22
00:00:48,020 --> 00:00:51,960
Here in this clip, you see the
Tin Man, Dorothy, and scarecrow

23
00:00:51,960 --> 00:00:53,520
as they head down
the yellow brick

24
00:00:53,520 --> 00:00:57,680
road, getting themselves all
worked up about lions and tigers

25
00:00:57,680 --> 00:00:59,860
and bears, and they
were interrupted

26
00:00:59,860 --> 00:01:02,780
by the roar of a
lion, which they later

27
00:01:02,780 --> 00:01:06,980
found out wasn't very brave, but
helped them get to the Emerald

28
00:01:06,980 --> 00:01:08,580
City and to the wizard.

29
00:01:08,580 --> 00:01:10,940
I'm hoping that this
adventure guide will

30
00:01:10,940 --> 00:01:17,340
help you feel empowered to use
some of these tools in Tableau

31
00:01:17,340 --> 00:01:20,780
to create and see
insights for your data.

32
00:01:20,780 --> 00:01:29,660
So we're going to
take a look at sorts--

33
00:01:29,660 --> 00:01:33,320
the data, the alphabetic
field, manual and nested.

34
00:01:33,320 --> 00:01:35,180
We're going to learn
about filters--

35
00:01:35,180 --> 00:01:38,780
the selection, wildcard,
condition, and top filters.

36
00:01:38,780 --> 00:01:41,260
We're going to touch just
a little bit on parameters

37
00:01:41,260 --> 00:01:44,200
in this adventure guide.

38
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:47,500
And then we'll round it
off with groups and sets.

39
00:01:47,500 --> 00:01:52,060
So let's dive first into
your adventure guide

40
00:01:52,060 --> 00:01:56,900
entitled advanced, sort,
filter, and set start.

41
00:01:56,900 --> 00:02:00,520
And you should find yourself
on the Overview tab.

42
00:02:00,520 --> 00:02:05,860
And so whenever you work in
business, order does matter.

43
00:02:05,860 --> 00:02:09,720
And Tableau gives you this power
to sort, filter, create groups,

44
00:02:09,720 --> 00:02:13,480
and create parameters, which
gives you a lot of flexibility

45
00:02:13,480 --> 00:02:15,120
with your data.

46
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:19,080
So let's go ahead and look at
this particular simple summary

47
00:02:19,080 --> 00:02:20,360
table.

48
00:02:20,360 --> 00:02:22,800
One of the features that
you're familiar with

49
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:29,240
is the ascending and descending
way to sort on the toolbar.

50
00:02:29,240 --> 00:02:32,480
So if you want to see the
smallest values on top

51
00:02:32,480 --> 00:02:38,360
and largest on bottom, then you
would click the ascending sort.

52
00:02:38,360 --> 00:02:41,840
If you want to see the
highest to lowest values,

53
00:02:41,840 --> 00:02:46,160
you would need to select
the descending sort.

54
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:49,020
If you want more
control of your sorting,

55
00:02:49,020 --> 00:02:51,480
then you need to open
up the sorting dialog

56
00:02:51,480 --> 00:02:53,800
box for a particular field.

57
00:02:53,800 --> 00:02:59,050
So in this case, you can see
I've got customer stayed on rows

58
00:02:59,050 --> 00:03:02,750
and there's been a
sort applied to that.

59
00:03:02,750 --> 00:03:06,450
I can see that because I've
got this icon right here.

60
00:03:06,450 --> 00:03:11,870
And if I do the dropdown arrow,
I can actually clear that sort.

61
00:03:11,870 --> 00:03:13,750
So now that icon is gone.

62
00:03:13,750 --> 00:03:18,370
But we want to have more
options for our sort.

63
00:03:18,370 --> 00:03:23,330
So I'll click the sort field
here, drag my dialog box off

64
00:03:23,330 --> 00:03:25,050
to the left here.

65
00:03:25,050 --> 00:03:29,570
And then you can see that
there are a variety of ways

66
00:03:29,570 --> 00:03:31,210
that you can sort by.

67
00:03:31,210 --> 00:03:35,010
So you can by your data,
alphabetic, field, manual,

68
00:03:35,010 --> 00:03:35,703
and nested.

69
00:03:35,703 --> 00:03:36,870
Let's just go through these.

70
00:03:36,870 --> 00:03:40,810
So to sort by your
data, now our data

71
00:03:40,810 --> 00:03:44,530
that we have showing in
this field is string data.

72
00:03:44,530 --> 00:03:48,210
So to sort string data,
you alphabetize it.

73
00:03:48,210 --> 00:03:53,970
So this particular
sort is the same

74
00:03:53,970 --> 00:03:56,990
as the second sort,
which is the alphabetic.

75
00:03:56,990 --> 00:04:00,710
However, if you were
to use a numeric field,

76
00:04:00,710 --> 00:04:02,310
then it would sort
by those numbers

77
00:04:02,310 --> 00:04:06,110
instead of the alphabetized.

78
00:04:06,110 --> 00:04:09,790
So then you also have the
ability to sort by field.

79
00:04:09,790 --> 00:04:14,710
And this is what this ascending
and descending quick commands

80
00:04:14,710 --> 00:04:17,589
or tools on the
toolbar do, that they

81
00:04:17,589 --> 00:04:19,050
do ascending and descending.

82
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:23,270
But in this dialog box, you
could change the field's name.

83
00:04:23,270 --> 00:04:25,270
Right now, we have order total.

84
00:04:25,270 --> 00:04:27,930
And you can also
change the aggregation.

85
00:04:27,930 --> 00:04:30,350
So let's just say
I'll go to average.

86
00:04:30,350 --> 00:04:34,370
Now notice in a sort,
it does it on the fly.

87
00:04:34,370 --> 00:04:35,950
I don't click apply.

88
00:04:35,950 --> 00:04:37,390
Nothing else.

89
00:04:37,390 --> 00:04:41,590
It just does it when I select
it within the dialog box.

90
00:04:41,590 --> 00:04:44,990
And so that's something that's
different than a filter.

91
00:04:44,990 --> 00:04:47,850
And we'll talk about that
and show that in a minute.

92
00:04:47,850 --> 00:04:49,750
But let's go back to sum here.

93
00:04:49,750 --> 00:04:52,590
And now I can see that
I've got from an ascending

94
00:04:52,590 --> 00:04:54,190
versus descending.

95
00:04:54,190 --> 00:04:56,370
And that's what we saw
here when we did this

96
00:04:56,370 --> 00:04:57,990
with the ascending
and descending.

97
00:04:57,990 --> 00:05:01,610
Now you also have the
option to do manual.

98
00:05:01,610 --> 00:05:04,090
So say, for instance, I'm
going to be presenting

99
00:05:04,090 --> 00:05:07,490
some data to some
representatives

100
00:05:07,490 --> 00:05:09,450
from the great state of Ohio.

101
00:05:09,450 --> 00:05:11,550
So I want to put
that at the very top.

102
00:05:11,550 --> 00:05:13,890
So I'll click that to be on top.

103
00:05:13,890 --> 00:05:19,250
And then I am going to
fly and go to Tennessee.

104
00:05:19,250 --> 00:05:22,770
And I want to have that
at the top as well.

105
00:05:22,770 --> 00:05:24,190
But I want it below Ohio.

106
00:05:24,190 --> 00:05:27,810
So you can see you can just
order, manually order or sort

107
00:05:27,810 --> 00:05:31,090
your data, which
can be very helpful.

108
00:05:31,090 --> 00:05:33,230
And then finally,
you have nested.

109
00:05:33,230 --> 00:05:35,430
And we'll talk about
that in just a moment.

110
00:05:35,430 --> 00:05:37,610
First of all, I want to
show you in the dialog box

111
00:05:37,610 --> 00:05:40,530
how you can also click
the Clear button.

112
00:05:40,530 --> 00:05:44,250
So by doing so removes
that icon in the pill

113
00:05:44,250 --> 00:05:46,930
and knows that there's
no sort being applied.

114
00:05:46,930 --> 00:05:51,970
So just to let you know, you
cannot sort by a dimension text

115
00:05:51,970 --> 00:05:52,730
length.

116
00:05:52,730 --> 00:05:56,510
You can only do data, the
alphabetic, the field, manual,

117
00:05:56,510 --> 00:05:57,770
and nested.

118
00:06:04,790 --> 00:06:12,670
So let's dive into
a nested sort here.

119
00:06:12,670 --> 00:06:17,950
And a nested sort is also
on this-- you'll find this

120
00:06:17,950 --> 00:06:20,830
on the tab entitled sort.

121
00:06:20,830 --> 00:06:24,550
And when you have a single
level of organization,

122
00:06:24,550 --> 00:06:27,470
like we just were looking
at that simple table,

123
00:06:27,470 --> 00:06:29,750
it's fairly
straightforward to sort.

124
00:06:29,750 --> 00:06:32,110
However, when you have multiple
levels of organization,

125
00:06:32,110 --> 00:06:35,550
then you need a special kind
of sort, and that nested sort.

126
00:06:35,550 --> 00:06:40,110
So this sheet has two different
levels of organization.

127
00:06:40,110 --> 00:06:42,710
On the rows shelf, you've
got product category

128
00:06:42,710 --> 00:06:45,550
with the bath,
gift, and olive oil.

129
00:06:45,550 --> 00:06:47,910
And then you also
have the sales region.

130
00:06:47,910 --> 00:06:52,030
And right now, these are
organized by alphabetical order.

131
00:06:52,030 --> 00:06:55,010
But let's say that I want to
leave the product categories

132
00:06:55,010 --> 00:06:56,590
in their current
alphabetical order,

133
00:06:56,590 --> 00:07:02,370
but I want to sort the sales
regions within each of them

134
00:07:02,370 --> 00:07:04,230
based on their sales total.

135
00:07:04,230 --> 00:07:06,730
So right now, they're
not sorted in that way.

136
00:07:06,730 --> 00:07:10,250
So to do that, I need
to create a nested sort.

137
00:07:10,250 --> 00:07:14,470
And in this case, the word
nested refers to a bird's nest.

138
00:07:14,470 --> 00:07:16,930
You have eggs in
the nest and then

139
00:07:16,930 --> 00:07:19,130
the bird sits on
top of the eggs.

140
00:07:19,130 --> 00:07:23,450
And then within the nest, you
have these multiple layers,

141
00:07:23,450 --> 00:07:24,650
if you will.

142
00:07:24,650 --> 00:07:27,590
So I want to sort
based on sales region.

143
00:07:27,590 --> 00:07:29,970
So I'm going to go to
the sales region pill

144
00:07:29,970 --> 00:07:33,450
and I'm going to do the
dropdown and select sort.

145
00:07:33,450 --> 00:07:37,050
Here I have all of those
sorts I just discussed.

146
00:07:37,050 --> 00:07:39,610
And I'm going to
select now nested.

147
00:07:39,610 --> 00:07:44,610
So here you can see that Tableau
is quickly determined the best

148
00:07:44,610 --> 00:07:48,490
type of sort that it believes
I want to do, and it's correct.

149
00:07:48,490 --> 00:07:51,980
I've got the field
name on order total

150
00:07:51,980 --> 00:07:54,700
and I have the
aggregation to be sum.

151
00:07:54,700 --> 00:07:56,680
Now I'm not going
to do ascending.

152
00:07:56,680 --> 00:07:58,980
I'm actually going to
change it to descending.

153
00:07:58,980 --> 00:08:07,820
So I want you to notice which
regions in your own view

154
00:08:07,820 --> 00:08:10,760
are the highest and the lowest.

155
00:08:14,820 --> 00:08:17,860
And so here can see
that the South Central

156
00:08:17,860 --> 00:08:22,540
East is the highest in every
region in terms of its product

157
00:08:22,540 --> 00:08:23,580
category.

158
00:08:23,580 --> 00:08:27,220
And then the North Central
West is the lowest.

159
00:08:27,220 --> 00:08:31,900
So one thing you might
recommend to maybe director

160
00:08:31,900 --> 00:08:36,500
is to see if the North Central
West representatives could

161
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:41,419
shadow the South Central East
to perhaps help them improve

162
00:08:41,419 --> 00:08:43,360
their sales and their outcomes.

163
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:46,920
So that is a nested sort.

164
00:08:50,440 --> 00:08:52,120
The next item we're
going to talk about

165
00:08:52,120 --> 00:08:55,520
is the power of a
filter and how filters

166
00:08:55,520 --> 00:08:57,400
are different than sorts.

167
00:08:57,400 --> 00:09:01,840
So when you save data
in the Tableau workbook,

168
00:09:01,840 --> 00:09:04,680
the program maintains
an internal list

169
00:09:04,680 --> 00:09:06,480
of all the values in the column.

170
00:09:06,480 --> 00:09:08,880
And so if you want
to filter a column so

171
00:09:08,880 --> 00:09:10,640
that only certain
values appear, you

172
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:13,040
can take advantage
of that internal list

173
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:14,480
by creating a filter.

174
00:09:14,480 --> 00:09:17,920
So let's go ahead and click on
the Filter tab on the bottom

175
00:09:17,920 --> 00:09:18,520
there.

176
00:09:18,520 --> 00:09:24,160
And you'll see I have a
very similar simple table.

177
00:09:24,160 --> 00:09:29,640
And what I want to do is I
want to see sales results only

178
00:09:29,640 --> 00:09:32,160
for a few of these
sales regions.

179
00:09:32,160 --> 00:09:36,360
And so I can drag the sales
region onto the filter shelf

180
00:09:36,360 --> 00:09:39,120
and then I'll see this
dialog box that opens up.

181
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:40,820
And you can see
there's options here.

182
00:09:40,820 --> 00:09:42,940
We have general,
we have wildcard,

183
00:09:42,940 --> 00:09:44,180
We have condition, and top.

184
00:09:44,180 --> 00:09:45,597
And we'll go through
all of those.

185
00:09:45,597 --> 00:09:47,400
But let's just check
out the general first.

186
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:50,100
You can see I've got
everything selected right now.

187
00:09:50,100 --> 00:09:54,060
I could click none and then
I can click all back again.

188
00:09:54,060 --> 00:09:57,520
I could deselect a
few of these regions.

189
00:09:57,520 --> 00:10:01,900
Here are the northeast and
northwest and click Apply.

190
00:10:01,900 --> 00:10:05,060
And then you can see what
happens within the table itself.

191
00:10:05,060 --> 00:10:07,780
I recommend as a best practice
when you're learning Tableau

192
00:10:07,780 --> 00:10:11,240
is to just keep the
filter's dialog box open

193
00:10:11,240 --> 00:10:14,140
and then just click Apply
to see what's happening.

194
00:10:14,140 --> 00:10:18,380
I can also use the exclude here.

195
00:10:18,380 --> 00:10:21,300
And when I hit
Apply, you'll notice

196
00:10:21,300 --> 00:10:27,380
that I have these
sales regions that are

197
00:10:27,380 --> 00:10:30,180
checked with a strikethrough.

198
00:10:30,180 --> 00:10:33,500
And so I know that only
the northeast and northwest

199
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:35,840
are showing because
the rest are excluded.

200
00:10:35,840 --> 00:10:39,500
So when I deselect that, that
strikethrough is now removed

201
00:10:39,500 --> 00:10:40,860
and I hit Apply.

202
00:10:40,860 --> 00:10:42,860
And now you can see that
I've got everything,

203
00:10:42,860 --> 00:10:45,420
except for the
northeast and northwest.

204
00:10:45,420 --> 00:10:49,760
So I'm going to go ahead and
just select them all and apply

205
00:10:49,760 --> 00:10:53,640
and we'll move down to
the next filter which

206
00:10:53,640 --> 00:10:56,060
is the wildcard filter.

207
00:10:56,060 --> 00:11:00,560
So wildcard lets you
limit the data to values

208
00:11:00,560 --> 00:11:02,680
that follow a specific pattern.

209
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:05,795
So if we look at our
data, the product category

210
00:11:05,795 --> 00:11:07,420
doesn't really have
a specific pattern.

211
00:11:07,420 --> 00:11:08,880
We only have three of those.

212
00:11:08,880 --> 00:11:11,740
But there is some patterns
in the sales region.

213
00:11:11,740 --> 00:11:15,560
And that's what I'm
going to look at.

214
00:11:15,560 --> 00:11:19,520
So let's go ahead and
click on the wildcard here.

215
00:11:19,520 --> 00:11:21,640
And you can see that
there are a few options.

216
00:11:21,640 --> 00:11:25,628
You have contains, start with,
ends with, and exactly matches.

217
00:11:25,628 --> 00:11:27,920
So let's start off with this
contains and just go ahead

218
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:29,720
and type in the word North.

219
00:11:29,720 --> 00:11:31,960
And then again,
we'll just hit Apply.

220
00:11:31,960 --> 00:11:36,400
And you'll see that it is
showing these regions that

221
00:11:36,400 --> 00:11:37,580
have the word north.

222
00:11:37,580 --> 00:11:39,880
Now you may have
noticed in my data

223
00:11:39,880 --> 00:11:42,960
that I'm missing some
regions that are in the north

224
00:11:42,960 --> 00:11:46,420
because I did not spell
out the whole name.

225
00:11:46,420 --> 00:11:48,340
So I'm going to just
clear that for a moment.

226
00:11:48,340 --> 00:11:49,590
So we can go back to our data.

227
00:11:49,590 --> 00:11:54,250
And you can see that I have
some with just the capital N.

228
00:11:54,250 --> 00:11:57,250
So I could do starts
with and I could just

229
00:11:57,250 --> 00:12:02,290
have an N. Notice it's not
uppercase or lowercase.

230
00:12:02,290 --> 00:12:03,470
And I can apply that.

231
00:12:03,470 --> 00:12:05,450
And now I've included that.

232
00:12:05,450 --> 00:12:08,890
Now as a rule of thumb, I
don't recommend doing filters

233
00:12:08,890 --> 00:12:11,530
on single letters.

234
00:12:11,530 --> 00:12:14,750
But in this case, the
data set is fairly small.

235
00:12:14,750 --> 00:12:19,290
So it does capture those
regions with just the letter N.

236
00:12:19,290 --> 00:12:24,890
You could also do ends with and
you could type in a word there.

237
00:12:24,890 --> 00:12:26,210
Let's hit Apply.

238
00:12:26,210 --> 00:12:28,530
And just having east there.

239
00:12:28,530 --> 00:12:33,310
And then exactly matches
you have to type in the word

240
00:12:33,310 --> 00:12:34,310
that you're looking for.

241
00:12:34,310 --> 00:12:37,410
This can be very helpful if
you just have a sea of data

242
00:12:37,410 --> 00:12:43,410
and you just need to find a
specific category or product

243
00:12:43,410 --> 00:12:46,270
or sales amount.

244
00:12:46,270 --> 00:12:49,190
So that's the wildcard.

245
00:12:49,190 --> 00:12:52,350
And you can see
it's a powerful tool

246
00:12:52,350 --> 00:12:54,870
to find what you need
to sort your data when

247
00:12:54,870 --> 00:12:56,270
you have those patterns.

248
00:12:56,270 --> 00:12:59,230
So I'm going to go ahead,
before we do this condition 1,

249
00:12:59,230 --> 00:13:03,430
I'm going to click OK here.

250
00:13:03,430 --> 00:13:07,570
And then I'm going to remove
product category from the row.

251
00:13:07,570 --> 00:13:09,670
I'm going to reshuffle
this a little bit.

252
00:13:09,670 --> 00:13:13,050
I'm going to remove sum here and
I'm going to remove this filter.

253
00:13:13,050 --> 00:13:16,890
So I'm just keeping that sales
category or sales region on row.

254
00:13:16,890 --> 00:13:22,270
And I'm going to add in this
sheet count onto my text here.

255
00:13:22,270 --> 00:13:26,990
So what does this is something
that Tableau does automatically.

256
00:13:26,990 --> 00:13:32,150
It counts the amount
of sales that occurred

257
00:13:32,150 --> 00:13:33,410
in each of the regions.

258
00:13:33,410 --> 00:13:37,210
So it's an additional measure
that Tableau has created.

259
00:13:37,210 --> 00:13:40,510
But we're going to use this
for that condition filter.

260
00:13:40,510 --> 00:13:46,290
So say I want to
determine whether or not

261
00:13:46,290 --> 00:13:51,290
or how many sales regions
have fewer than 500 sales.

262
00:13:51,290 --> 00:13:59,570
So I want to go into here,
go into sales region,

263
00:13:59,570 --> 00:14:01,970
go into condition now.

264
00:14:01,970 --> 00:14:05,990
And you can see I want
to select by field.

265
00:14:05,990 --> 00:14:09,510
So I'm going to use that
sheet 1 that I've selected.

266
00:14:09,510 --> 00:14:11,010
Count is correct.

267
00:14:11,010 --> 00:14:14,890
And now I need to select
less than or equal to.

268
00:14:14,890 --> 00:14:17,770
And then I'm going to put 500.

269
00:14:17,770 --> 00:14:20,510
Now before I do this, I want
you to do it on your own.

270
00:14:20,510 --> 00:14:24,570
And then tell me
how many regions

271
00:14:24,570 --> 00:14:26,670
have fewer than 500 sales.

272
00:14:29,650 --> 00:14:31,890
All right, I'm
going to click OK.

273
00:14:31,890 --> 00:14:34,170
And you can see that
there are indeed

274
00:14:34,170 --> 00:14:36,610
only three-- the north
central west, northwest,

275
00:14:36,610 --> 00:14:38,290
and the south central west.

276
00:14:38,290 --> 00:14:41,130
Now I'm going to go back
and edit that filter.

277
00:14:41,130 --> 00:14:44,130
And I could change
that to be 700.

278
00:14:44,130 --> 00:14:46,830
I might want to
include more in there.

279
00:14:46,830 --> 00:14:50,630
So now I can see that I've
got seven-- actually six,

280
00:14:50,630 --> 00:14:57,910
excuse me, regions that
have sales less than 700.

281
00:14:57,910 --> 00:15:04,590
So that is the condition
filter, if you will.

282
00:15:04,590 --> 00:15:10,870
So then the final one
is the top filter.

283
00:15:10,870 --> 00:15:13,890
And that is a way to see
values at the very top.

284
00:15:13,890 --> 00:15:16,050
Now this is a very
small dataset.

285
00:15:16,050 --> 00:15:18,470
But we'll just show how
this works for there.

286
00:15:18,470 --> 00:15:20,550
I'm going to go
ahead and hit Cancel,

287
00:15:20,550 --> 00:15:22,350
I'm going to reorganize this.

288
00:15:22,350 --> 00:15:25,910
I'm going to remove sales
regions from the filter

289
00:15:25,910 --> 00:15:30,190
and I'm going to also
remove sales region

290
00:15:30,190 --> 00:15:31,690
from the row and the count.

291
00:15:31,690 --> 00:15:33,990
So we're just going to
clear our sheet off here.

292
00:15:33,990 --> 00:15:39,430
And I'm going to add
customer state to my row

293
00:15:39,430 --> 00:15:42,090
and I'm going to do
order total onto.

294
00:15:42,090 --> 00:15:45,570
So back to my simple
summary table here.

295
00:15:45,570 --> 00:15:48,890
So say like I want to
display five states that

296
00:15:48,890 --> 00:15:52,390
provided the most value, then
I can create that top filter.

297
00:15:52,390 --> 00:15:57,530
So I'm going to drag customer
state to the filters here.

298
00:15:57,530 --> 00:15:58,970
Go to the top.

299
00:15:58,970 --> 00:16:03,550
And now I can see that I can
actually again select by field.

300
00:16:03,550 --> 00:16:05,730
And I have top.

301
00:16:05,730 --> 00:16:09,930
Tableau automatically puts
10, but I can put down 5 here.

302
00:16:09,930 --> 00:16:12,130
And it does it by order
total, which I have

303
00:16:12,130 --> 00:16:14,450
already as my field and sum.

304
00:16:14,450 --> 00:16:19,890
So you can apply that and then
simply see how many those are.

305
00:16:19,890 --> 00:16:24,650
So I could change
this to be 7, 20.

306
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:25,990
And this could help in my view.

307
00:16:25,990 --> 00:16:30,050
Maybe I want to create some kind
of a chart or visualization that

308
00:16:30,050 --> 00:16:31,530
will be added to
a dashboard that

309
00:16:31,530 --> 00:16:34,810
has only this amount
of the data showing.

310
00:16:34,810 --> 00:16:41,100
So that's how you use the
filters within Tableau.

311
00:16:41,100 --> 00:16:49,360
Next one we're going to do is to
add a parameter to the filter.

312
00:16:49,360 --> 00:16:53,980
Now this is where we begin
to see some power of Tableau.

313
00:16:53,980 --> 00:16:57,980
And we'll go ahead to
our Tableau worksheet

314
00:16:57,980 --> 00:17:01,360
here and click on the
filter and the parameter.

315
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:02,900
And you can see
what I have here.

316
00:17:02,900 --> 00:17:05,099
I have a tree map.

317
00:17:05,099 --> 00:17:12,980
And the thing to remember about
parameters in terms of filters

318
00:17:12,980 --> 00:17:15,740
is they act sometimes
very similarly.

319
00:17:15,740 --> 00:17:23,220
But a filter has to use the
data that is within the source.

320
00:17:23,220 --> 00:17:25,740
Parameters are powerful
tools because they're not

321
00:17:25,740 --> 00:17:28,620
dependent on what's
inside the data.

322
00:17:28,620 --> 00:17:31,620
You can go outside of that.

323
00:17:31,620 --> 00:17:34,780
Parameters will be
used more extensively.

324
00:17:34,780 --> 00:17:37,000
And the advanced
data 5400 course.

325
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:39,220
You might even decide
to use some parameters

326
00:17:39,220 --> 00:17:41,640
for your project,
which would be awesome.

327
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:44,840
But I want you to remember
that a parameter is not exactly

328
00:17:44,840 --> 00:17:46,320
the same as a filter.

329
00:17:46,320 --> 00:17:49,160
A filter is tied to
the data and can only

330
00:17:49,160 --> 00:17:51,280
reflect what's in the data.

331
00:17:51,280 --> 00:17:53,840
A parameter can take
anything you'd like and do

332
00:17:53,840 --> 00:17:54,700
whatever you'd like.

333
00:17:54,700 --> 00:17:56,920
And we're going to try and
do a little bit of that

334
00:17:56,920 --> 00:18:00,720
here within this
very short demo.

335
00:18:00,720 --> 00:18:02,960
So we're looking
at this tree map.

336
00:18:02,960 --> 00:18:06,480
And you can see that
it is organized,

337
00:18:06,480 --> 00:18:08,760
of course, by the quantities.

338
00:18:08,760 --> 00:18:11,600
We have the extra virgin
olive oil-- bold 12

339
00:18:11,600 --> 00:18:14,560
pack being the
most sold and then

340
00:18:14,560 --> 00:18:17,640
the chili extra virgin olive
oil, et cetera, et cetera.

341
00:18:17,640 --> 00:18:19,680
You can see how that lays out.

342
00:18:19,680 --> 00:18:24,360
So what I'm going to do
is create a top filter.

343
00:18:24,360 --> 00:18:25,520
We just did that.

344
00:18:25,520 --> 00:18:27,440
And I'm going to
add a parameter so I

345
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:34,680
have control over how many I
want to see within a dialog box.

346
00:18:34,680 --> 00:18:40,260
So I'm going to, first
of all, go into--

347
00:18:40,260 --> 00:18:42,560
and I'm going to do
that based on quantity.

348
00:18:42,560 --> 00:18:45,560
I'm going to create the
parameter based on quantity.

349
00:18:45,560 --> 00:18:48,740
So I'm going to go into
measure names under quantity

350
00:18:48,740 --> 00:18:52,660
and do the down arrow.

351
00:18:52,660 --> 00:18:53,420
Let's see.

352
00:18:53,420 --> 00:18:55,400
And then I'm going
to hit Create.

353
00:18:55,400 --> 00:18:58,200
And you can see I can create a
calculated field, group, bins.

354
00:18:58,200 --> 00:19:00,820
But I'm going to
create a parameter.

355
00:19:00,820 --> 00:19:02,000
And I can rename that.

356
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:08,540
Let's just do-- you can
rename that whatever you want.

357
00:19:08,540 --> 00:19:13,260
Now integer is correct
for this because the way

358
00:19:13,260 --> 00:19:18,380
that this data is created is,
although I have 12 olive oil

359
00:19:18,380 --> 00:19:20,520
bottles, they're
all in one pack.

360
00:19:20,520 --> 00:19:23,740
So I can't order 1
and 1/2 of those.

361
00:19:23,740 --> 00:19:25,073
I have to order a whole.

362
00:19:25,073 --> 00:19:26,240
So integer is the right one.

363
00:19:26,240 --> 00:19:28,840
But you can see there's
others, there's strings,

364
00:19:28,840 --> 00:19:30,960
there's Boolean,
date, date, and time.

365
00:19:30,960 --> 00:19:32,600
And then there's also float.

366
00:19:32,600 --> 00:19:36,980
So if I were going to have just
numerical values of a variety,

367
00:19:36,980 --> 00:19:38,820
I would just hit float.

368
00:19:38,820 --> 00:19:40,820
But for this case,
I'll have integers.

369
00:19:40,820 --> 00:19:42,180
The current value is 1.

370
00:19:42,180 --> 00:19:43,100
This is all great.

371
00:19:43,100 --> 00:19:44,940
Now allowable values.

372
00:19:44,940 --> 00:19:46,960
This is what I'm going
to see in my view.

373
00:19:46,960 --> 00:19:49,600
I can have all of them,
I can have the list,

374
00:19:49,600 --> 00:19:51,263
or I can have a range.

375
00:19:51,263 --> 00:19:53,180
And this is where you
can do some exploration.

376
00:19:53,180 --> 00:19:55,680
But I'm going to have
a range in this case.

377
00:19:55,680 --> 00:20:00,280
Now the range of values,
the minimum and maximum

378
00:20:00,280 --> 00:20:03,480
actually show exactly what's
in the data right now.

379
00:20:03,480 --> 00:20:07,720
So it's using the
data to recommend

380
00:20:07,720 --> 00:20:11,220
that the minimum would be 1
and the maximum would be 14.

381
00:20:11,220 --> 00:20:12,720
However, again,
this is a parameter.

382
00:20:12,720 --> 00:20:14,960
I can do whatever I want.

383
00:20:14,960 --> 00:20:16,820
So I could have this be 100.

384
00:20:16,820 --> 00:20:19,400
Now that would be a lot
of blank screen there.

385
00:20:19,400 --> 00:20:22,400
So instead I'm going to
move this just to 15, just

386
00:20:22,400 --> 00:20:24,520
so I could see the full range.

387
00:20:24,520 --> 00:20:27,200
And so it's important
to know that there is

388
00:20:27,200 --> 00:20:30,420
flexibility in the parameter.

389
00:20:30,420 --> 00:20:32,600
It's not tied to your data.

390
00:20:32,600 --> 00:20:37,370
So let's just say that you
have a dataset with six values,

391
00:20:37,370 --> 00:20:39,690
but you want to show more.

392
00:20:39,690 --> 00:20:42,570
So what parameter do you
need to change in order

393
00:20:42,570 --> 00:20:46,890
to display the
additional values?

394
00:20:46,890 --> 00:20:49,190
Hopefully, you
selected that, yes,

395
00:20:49,190 --> 00:20:52,770
you need to increase the
maximum range of values

396
00:20:52,770 --> 00:20:54,030
to be one higher.

397
00:20:54,030 --> 00:20:57,290
So that's what we did
here in this example.

398
00:20:57,290 --> 00:21:00,330
So let's go ahead and click OK.

399
00:21:00,330 --> 00:21:02,130
And now you can see
in the parameters,

400
00:21:02,130 --> 00:21:07,610
we have now a new section
here in the sidebar.

401
00:21:07,610 --> 00:21:14,490
And we're going to drag the
product name to the filters card

402
00:21:14,490 --> 00:21:15,530
here.

403
00:21:15,530 --> 00:21:18,410
We're going to go
to our top filter.

404
00:21:18,410 --> 00:21:20,890
We're going to do by field.

405
00:21:20,890 --> 00:21:22,990
And we're going to
maintain top here.

406
00:21:22,990 --> 00:21:24,730
But instead of
putting in a number,

407
00:21:24,730 --> 00:21:27,677
we're going to just
select a parameter.

408
00:21:27,677 --> 00:21:29,510
And it's the parameter
that we just created.

409
00:21:29,510 --> 00:21:31,970
So it's quantity parameter.

410
00:21:31,970 --> 00:21:35,050
We want it still by quantity
and sum, cetera, et cetera,

411
00:21:35,050 --> 00:21:35,770
et cetera.

412
00:21:35,770 --> 00:21:37,870
And we're going to hit OK.

413
00:21:37,870 --> 00:21:39,730
So now what's happened?

414
00:21:39,730 --> 00:21:43,550
It's gone to a full
just singular box here.

415
00:21:43,550 --> 00:21:47,290
That's because it's showing
my very top single parameter.

416
00:21:47,290 --> 00:21:49,133
And I need to be
able to show that.

417
00:21:49,133 --> 00:21:50,550
So in order to
show that, I'm just

418
00:21:50,550 --> 00:21:52,390
going to go to my
parameters box.

419
00:21:52,390 --> 00:21:54,910
I'm going to click that
and say show parameter.

420
00:21:54,910 --> 00:21:59,590
And now what I have is I have
the ability to move that.

421
00:21:59,590 --> 00:22:04,550
So see now I can say within my
presentation or my dashboard,

422
00:22:04,550 --> 00:22:07,130
how many parameters affect that.

423
00:22:07,130 --> 00:22:11,077
And those can affect other
charts within a dashboard.

424
00:22:11,077 --> 00:22:12,410
And we'll talk about that later.

425
00:22:12,410 --> 00:22:16,520
But this is how you
create a parameter.

426
00:22:16,520 --> 00:22:18,630
Now let's see.

427
00:22:18,630 --> 00:22:21,190
The last two sections
I'm going to talk about

428
00:22:21,190 --> 00:22:23,670
are groups and sets.

429
00:22:23,670 --> 00:22:31,670
So let's go first to groups
and go to our group tab here.

430
00:22:31,670 --> 00:22:36,070
And when you collect business
data, the more detail,

431
00:22:36,070 --> 00:22:36,810
the better.

432
00:22:36,810 --> 00:22:40,370
But there might be times when
you want to combine two elements

433
00:22:40,370 --> 00:22:41,350
or more into one.

434
00:22:41,350 --> 00:22:44,490
And so here we have this
simple table visualization

435
00:22:44,490 --> 00:22:47,450
that summarizes total
sales by region.

436
00:22:47,450 --> 00:22:50,370
However, if we look at the
north central east and north

437
00:22:50,370 --> 00:22:53,250
central west, you'll see
that this particular region

438
00:22:53,250 --> 00:22:58,310
has a lot fewer sales
than the east does.

439
00:22:58,310 --> 00:23:01,510
And so I'd like to combine
those into a single group.

440
00:23:01,510 --> 00:23:02,870
So I'll do that by selecting it.

441
00:23:02,870 --> 00:23:05,870
And I'll hold down the
Control or Shift key,

442
00:23:05,870 --> 00:23:09,750
depending on if you are a Mac
or PC to select both of those.

443
00:23:09,750 --> 00:23:12,890
And when you do that,
then a dialog box comes up

444
00:23:12,890 --> 00:23:15,610
and you can see that, if
you use the paper clip,

445
00:23:15,610 --> 00:23:17,190
it will show you group members.

446
00:23:17,190 --> 00:23:19,570
And I can hit the
paper clip and it

447
00:23:19,570 --> 00:23:24,170
will combine those two together
and also create a group here

448
00:23:24,170 --> 00:23:25,710
in the dimensions pane.

449
00:23:25,710 --> 00:23:32,630
So note how many sales, both
the north central east and north

450
00:23:32,630 --> 00:23:36,910
central west region had in
terms of combined sales.

451
00:23:36,910 --> 00:23:41,590
So if I want to compare this
group to the rest of the sales

452
00:23:41,590 --> 00:23:45,070
regions, then I can click
this down arrow right here

453
00:23:45,070 --> 00:23:47,950
and I could click include other.

454
00:23:47,950 --> 00:23:53,510
By doing that, I will
group the other categories,

455
00:23:53,510 --> 00:23:56,750
the other sales regions
and compare that

456
00:23:56,750 --> 00:23:58,210
to that sales region.

457
00:23:58,210 --> 00:24:01,150
So to deselect that, you just
go back and unselect that

458
00:24:01,150 --> 00:24:02,870
and then you're back
to where you're at.

459
00:24:02,870 --> 00:24:09,270
The last item of this
adventure guide are sets.

460
00:24:09,270 --> 00:24:12,670
So let's go to our sets.

461
00:24:12,670 --> 00:24:14,830
Tab here on our worksheet.

462
00:24:14,830 --> 00:24:17,810
And sets are
different than groups.

463
00:24:17,810 --> 00:24:20,330
Sets are a combination of items.

464
00:24:20,330 --> 00:24:22,470
So again, kind of similar
to groups, but they

465
00:24:22,470 --> 00:24:23,990
have a different power.

466
00:24:23,990 --> 00:24:26,190
And you'll see
that they actually

467
00:24:26,190 --> 00:24:28,950
act a little bit differently,
especially when you're

468
00:24:28,950 --> 00:24:33,710
trying to do order totals
or to apply them as filters.

469
00:24:33,710 --> 00:24:37,450
So let's go ahead and make the
north central east and north

470
00:24:37,450 --> 00:24:41,050
central west into a set.

471
00:24:41,050 --> 00:24:42,570
So instead of doing
the paper clip,

472
00:24:42,570 --> 00:24:45,830
we'll do this Venn
diagram circle here

473
00:24:45,830 --> 00:24:47,490
and we'll say create set.

474
00:24:47,490 --> 00:24:51,250
Now here I can control
what I want my set.

475
00:24:51,250 --> 00:24:55,290
I can remove items here or I
can exclude them, et cetera.

476
00:24:55,290 --> 00:24:57,022
I can add to the filter
shelf right away.

477
00:24:57,022 --> 00:24:58,230
But we'll do that separately.

478
00:24:58,230 --> 00:24:59,810
I'll just say OK.

479
00:24:59,810 --> 00:25:01,930
Now notice what's
different here.

480
00:25:01,930 --> 00:25:06,210
When you did it for groups, it
combined them within the view.

481
00:25:06,210 --> 00:25:10,450
When you did it for sets, it
actually just created a set

482
00:25:10,450 --> 00:25:12,070
here on the data pane.

483
00:25:12,070 --> 00:25:15,890
So different sort of
attributes that are happening

484
00:25:15,890 --> 00:25:18,730
between groups and sets.

485
00:25:18,730 --> 00:25:24,150
So let's go ahead and
actually make a second set.

486
00:25:24,150 --> 00:25:26,410
I'm going to do
this one right here.

487
00:25:26,410 --> 00:25:29,130
And I'm going to create
this as a set too.

488
00:25:29,130 --> 00:25:35,080
So I'm actually going to
call this the south region.

489
00:25:35,080 --> 00:25:35,580
OK.

490
00:25:35,580 --> 00:25:48,920
And then I'm going to
rename this one too.

491
00:25:54,460 --> 00:25:59,140
I'm going to call
this the north region.

492
00:25:59,140 --> 00:26:01,040
All right.

493
00:26:01,040 --> 00:26:04,940
So here I have my
data and now I'm

